1
00:00:35,999 --> 00:00:38,824
Another exhausting night shift.

2
00:00:39,145 --> 00:00:41,345
Let's head home and get some rest.

3
00:00:41,471 --> 00:00:42,771
Already rested.

4
00:00:43,236 --> 00:00:44,290
Huh?

5
00:00:44,290 --> 00:00:45,952
I just napped. That's enough.

6
00:00:46,123 --> 00:00:50,510
What are you saying? We have more staff now.
Don't push yourself.

7
00:00:50,510 --> 00:00:52,792
I'm not. Being here is easiest for me.

8
00:00:54,520 --> 00:00:55,897
She's right.

9
00:00:57,429 --> 00:01:02,303
Anno, go rest. That's an order.

10
00:01:02,682 --> 00:01:04,575
Dr. Daikoku, what's gotten into you?

11
00:01:04,575 --> 00:01:05,962
Director's orders.

12
00:01:06,402 --> 00:01:07,606
The director?

13
00:01:07,682 --> 00:01:11,376
The work reform law for doctors
went into effect last year, remember?

14
00:01:11,810 --> 00:01:15,870
They looked the other way due to
short staffing, but not anymore.

15
00:01:15,870 --> 00:01:16,903
Not interested.

16
00:01:16,903 --> 00:01:20,975
This isn't about your interest.
If they find out, I'm the one in trouble.

17
00:01:20,975 --> 00:01:22,530
I'm fine. I'm eating.

18
00:01:22,590 --> 00:01:25,270
What? No, that's not the—

19
00:01:26,308 --> 00:01:29,241
Hey! Huh?

20
00:01:30,801 --> 00:01:32,256
Stretcher coming through!

21
00:01:32,888 --> 00:01:37,512
Lower abdominal pain.
BP 123 over 71, O2 sat 96%.

22
00:01:37,512 --> 00:01:38,712
Right.

23
00:01:40,229 --> 00:01:43,855
Can you move? Okay, let's get you up.
Nice and slow. There we go.

24
00:01:46,003 --> 00:01:47,214
He's all yours.

25
00:01:47,860 --> 00:01:52,909
First, let's check his temperature
and get him on the monitor.

26
00:01:52,909 --> 00:01:54,136
Yes, Doctor.

27
00:01:54,514 --> 00:01:56,956
Excuse me. Pardon me.

28
00:01:57,516 --> 00:02:00,056
What's next? Orders, please.

29
00:02:01,109 --> 00:02:04,750
Uh, first start an IV line
and fluids, and...

30
00:02:05,890 --> 00:02:07,090
Uh...

31
00:02:07,381 --> 00:02:10,083
He falls apart without Dr. Ashura, huh?

32
00:02:10,083 --> 00:02:11,332
Yeah.

33
00:02:12,256 --> 00:02:14,180
Draw blood before starting fluids.

34
00:02:15,191 --> 00:02:17,423
Dr. Anno? You're still here?

35
00:02:17,423 --> 00:02:18,856
Kid, ultrasound. Now.

36
00:02:18,868 --> 00:02:22,269
Back to "Kid," I see. Got it.

37
00:02:22,349 --> 00:02:23,847
Shouldn't you be going home?

38
00:02:23,847 --> 00:02:26,032
Director Tamon will be furious with you.

39
00:02:26,032 --> 00:02:27,069
Ow!

40
00:02:27,069 --> 00:02:28,715
Not if nobody tells him.

41
00:02:30,536 --> 00:02:31,798
Not so fast.

42
00:02:33,547 --> 00:02:35,179
Why are you here?

43
00:02:35,496 --> 00:02:39,258
Your hours are about to exceed the limit.
Go home and rest.

44
00:02:39,376 --> 00:02:41,488
I can't leave when I have patients.

45
00:02:46,433 --> 00:02:49,773
Dr. Yakushiji, that patient
has appendicitis, correct?

46
00:02:50,025 --> 00:02:54,492
Y-Yes. The appendix is swollen
to about 13 millimeters.

47
00:02:54,527 --> 00:02:56,163
Can you handle the surgery?

48
00:02:56,880 --> 00:02:59,804
If it's appendicitis, I can do it.

49
00:03:00,092 --> 00:03:02,972
Sounds like you're not needed here today.

50
00:03:15,767 --> 00:03:19,100
Dr. Anno didn't look too happy about that.

51
00:03:19,100 --> 00:03:22,073
She never stops working
as long as there are patients.

52
00:03:22,073 --> 00:03:24,946
I worry she'll burn herself out.

53
00:03:24,946 --> 00:03:29,296
Well, I can't say
I don't understand how she feels.

54
00:03:30,446 --> 00:03:33,626
When we were young,
everyone was like that.

55
00:03:34,867 --> 00:03:39,121
Called in at all hours,
practically living at the hospital.

56
00:03:39,348 --> 00:03:42,267
I even nearly fell asleep
during surgery once.

57
00:03:43,513 --> 00:03:44,911
During surgery?

58
00:03:45,640 --> 00:03:49,587
We just figured that's what it meant
to work in Emergency Medicine.

59
00:03:50,548 --> 00:03:51,588
But...

60
00:03:51,588 --> 00:03:53,220
I should get back to work.

61
00:03:53,220 --> 00:03:57,210
- I have lab orders to send out.
- I'll do my ICU rounds then.

62
00:03:58,892 --> 00:04:01,283
It was just getting good!

63
00:04:16,766 --> 00:04:18,566
She looks happy to be working.

64
00:04:19,172 --> 00:04:21,207
She never went home.

65
00:04:21,768 --> 00:04:24,054
Does Dr. Anno even have a home?

66
00:04:26,306 --> 00:04:27,534
Oh, sorry.

67
00:04:27,859 --> 00:04:29,197
Of course you do.

68
00:04:31,873 --> 00:04:33,100
Incoming.

69
00:04:33,547 --> 00:04:34,747
Huh?

70
00:04:35,983 --> 00:04:37,027
Yes?

71
00:04:37,027 --> 00:04:40,818
Male, 60s, fell from the third floor.
Requesting admission.

72
00:04:40,818 --> 00:04:41,845
A fall.

73
00:04:41,845 --> 00:04:43,165
Bring him in now.

74
00:04:49,080 --> 00:04:51,835
Dr. Ashura

75
00:04:58,341 --> 00:04:59,626
Stretcher coming through!

76
00:04:59,626 --> 00:05:00,835
Turning!

77
00:05:01,909 --> 00:05:02,946
On three.

78
00:05:02,946 --> 00:05:04,149
One, two, three!

79
00:05:04,670 --> 00:05:06,315
Call for X-ray and get an IV in!

80
00:05:06,315 --> 00:05:08,281
- Starting an IV.
- Cutting clothes.

81
00:05:09,019 --> 00:05:10,256
Ultrasound, now.

82
00:05:21,370 --> 00:05:26,250
His wife says he may have slipped
on the balcony.

83
00:05:26,483 --> 00:05:27,523
The balcony?

84
00:05:27,523 --> 00:05:28,563
Yes.

85
00:05:28,563 --> 00:05:34,417
She didn't actually see him fall, though.
Her behavior seemed a bit off to me.

86
00:05:35,835 --> 00:05:38,463
Understood. Treatment comes first.

87
00:05:38,463 --> 00:05:39,667
Please.

88
00:05:47,264 --> 00:05:48,300
Status?

89
00:05:48,300 --> 00:05:50,287
Severe right pulmonary contusion.

90
00:05:52,425 --> 00:05:54,930
O2 sat's 83 on 15 liters
by reservoir mask.

91
00:05:54,930 --> 00:05:57,810
- Intubating. Kid, prep sedation.
- Yes, ma'am!

92
00:06:02,838 --> 00:06:04,531
N-No...

93
00:06:07,279 --> 00:06:09,383
That's enough.

94
00:06:12,906 --> 00:06:16,882
Don't do anything more.

95
00:06:27,393 --> 00:06:28,641
Dr. Anno.

96
00:06:30,810 --> 00:06:32,600
- V-fib!
- Charge the defibrillator!

97
00:06:32,600 --> 00:06:33,819
Got it!

98
00:06:35,245 --> 00:06:36,474
Charged and ready.

99
00:06:37,939 --> 00:06:39,174
Clear!

100
00:06:45,209 --> 00:06:46,240
No response.

101
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:48,173
- Again. Charge to 200.
- Got it.

102
00:06:48,173 --> 00:06:49,502
Stop it, please!

103
00:06:51,200 --> 00:06:54,640
Please, just do as my husband wished.

104
00:06:57,667 --> 00:06:59,667
My husband has terminal cancer.

105
00:07:01,010 --> 00:07:05,686
Even if you save him now,
he doesn't have long to live.

106
00:07:07,296 --> 00:07:10,108
Please just let him go in peace.

107
00:07:25,009 --> 00:07:29,716
Anno, the patient's family doesn't want
any further treatment.

108
00:07:31,882 --> 00:07:33,582
Stop...

109
00:07:34,489 --> 00:07:37,771
Emergency Medicine exists to save lives!

110
00:07:38,189 --> 00:07:41,471
That's why I will never give up on a life!

111
00:08:00,615 --> 00:08:02,653
Heartbeat restored. Prep for intubation.

112
00:08:02,653 --> 00:08:03,873
Okay.

113
00:08:11,937 --> 00:08:16,301
His body is still saying
it doesn't want to die.

114
00:08:33,313 --> 00:08:36,133
What? Dr. Ashura actually did that?

115
00:08:37,153 --> 00:08:39,849
She went ahead and saved him.

116
00:08:40,718 --> 00:08:46,379
Once patients are brought to the ER,
our duty is to save them.

117
00:08:46,428 --> 00:08:52,316
True. Even with terminal cancer, he wasn't
brought in because the cancer worsened.

118
00:08:53,286 --> 00:08:55,506
Still, something bothers me.

119
00:08:57,486 --> 00:09:01,682
Does an adult really just
fall off a balcony that easily?

120
00:09:22,225 --> 00:09:24,349
That's enough.

121
00:09:24,349 --> 00:09:27,737
Don't do anything more.

122
00:09:27,737 --> 00:09:30,307
Please just let him go in peace.

123
00:09:40,646 --> 00:09:44,520
Dr. Anno, Mr. Hashimoto is awake.

124
00:09:47,060 --> 00:09:48,100
Got it.

125
00:09:48,100 --> 00:09:49,300
I'll come too.

126
00:09:49,326 --> 00:09:50,536
Anno, wait.

127
00:09:51,695 --> 00:09:53,016
Don't go.

128
00:09:53,979 --> 00:09:55,425
I'll go instead.

129
00:09:56,546 --> 00:09:57,748
What do you mean?

130
00:09:58,347 --> 00:10:03,195
Right now, your presence
would only stress him out.

131
00:10:04,405 --> 00:10:07,620
You're off his case from now on.

132
00:10:09,666 --> 00:10:12,441
It's not just for Mr. Hashimoto's sake.

133
00:10:13,687 --> 00:10:16,305
It's better for you too, Anno.

134
00:10:20,583 --> 00:10:24,443
He's my patient.

135
00:10:27,546 --> 00:10:30,626
Doctor, wait!

136
00:10:50,433 --> 00:10:54,994
Sorry for causing you trouble again.

137
00:10:56,392 --> 00:11:00,552
Don't apologize. I'm fine.

138
00:11:01,375 --> 00:11:07,267
I wish I could've just died back there.

139
00:11:07,833 --> 00:11:10,505
Don't say that.

140
00:11:11,098 --> 00:11:13,732
It's not like the cancer's
going to be cured.

141
00:11:16,073 --> 00:11:20,293
There's no point
in living any longer.

142
00:11:29,240 --> 00:11:32,645
Vitals look stable. I'm examining him.

143
00:11:33,202 --> 00:11:40,106
Why did you treat me?
I told you not to do anything.

144
00:11:42,683 --> 00:11:48,372
My wife asked you
not to treat me too.

145
00:11:53,779 --> 00:11:59,026
All you did was prolong my life.

146
00:11:59,026 --> 00:12:02,212
Don't fool yourself
into thinking you saved me.

147
00:12:02,212 --> 00:12:04,280
Mr. Hashimoto, please calm down.

148
00:12:04,280 --> 00:12:05,646
Shut up.

149
00:12:08,952 --> 00:12:13,577
You think you helped me,

150
00:12:13,913 --> 00:12:17,974
but you took away my last hope.

151
00:12:19,670 --> 00:12:20,703
It's okay.

152
00:12:20,703 --> 00:12:23,605
Mr. Hashimoto, take a deep breath.

153
00:12:23,610 --> 00:12:24,883
Mr. Hashimoto.

154
00:12:28,793 --> 00:12:31,693
Nothing to say for yourself?

155
00:12:33,973 --> 00:12:36,584
Hit too close to home, didn't I?

156
00:12:41,056 --> 00:12:46,886
You trampled on your patient's wishes.
You'll burn in hell for this.

157
00:12:55,453 --> 00:12:57,526
I can't stand the sight of you.

158
00:13:00,616 --> 00:13:02,407
Get out. Now.

159
00:13:18,506 --> 00:13:19,972
Dr. Anno.

160
00:13:22,759 --> 00:13:24,916
Why did you go see Mr. Hashimoto?

161
00:13:28,121 --> 00:13:34,580
Why do you reach out
when you know he'll push you away?

162
00:13:39,419 --> 00:13:41,123
None of your business, Kid.

163
00:14:03,100 --> 00:14:07,097
Leave that patient to another doctor.

164
00:14:08,609 --> 00:14:11,496
I have a responsibility
to see his treatment through.

165
00:14:12,501 --> 00:14:16,107
I can't abandon a patient
I've already saved.

166
00:14:18,015 --> 00:14:24,100
I understand, but that sense of duty
will destroy you someday.

167
00:14:28,946 --> 00:14:32,567
I once knew a doctor
a lot like you, Anno.

168
00:14:34,573 --> 00:14:38,268
Strong sense of duty, just like you.
Skilled, too.

169
00:14:39,920 --> 00:14:44,455
No matter how dire the situation,
that doctor always fought to save lives.

170
00:14:44,651 --> 00:14:46,572
That's expected of an ER doctor.

171
00:14:48,157 --> 00:14:54,663
That's what they said too, sacrificing
sleep and health for their patients.

172
00:14:56,786 --> 00:14:58,114
But...

173
00:14:59,085 --> 00:15:04,011
eventually, both mind and body
passed their breaking point,

174
00:15:05,312 --> 00:15:08,499
and they burned out and quit medicine.

175
00:15:13,463 --> 00:15:15,666
I don't want that for you.

176
00:15:19,790 --> 00:15:21,280
That won't happen to me.

177
00:15:22,063 --> 00:15:25,117
That overconfidence will be your downfall.

178
00:15:30,215 --> 00:15:33,731
Learn to step back
instead of losing yourself in patients.

179
00:15:35,296 --> 00:15:38,402
Keep this up and you won't
be able to practice medicine.

180
00:15:46,763 --> 00:15:50,490
Stay away from that patient.
That's an order.

181
00:15:52,070 --> 00:15:57,450
Beyond that point lies hell for you, Anno.

182
00:16:10,780 --> 00:16:13,776
Do you think Dr. Anno's okay?

183
00:16:15,312 --> 00:16:16,975
Who knows?

184
00:16:32,462 --> 00:16:34,699
Taishaku General Hospital ER.

185
00:16:34,699 --> 00:16:38,902
Female in her twenties, apparent
sleeping pill overdose. Requesting intake.

186
00:16:38,902 --> 00:16:39,929
What should we do?

187
00:16:39,929 --> 00:16:41,233
- Accept her.
- Okay.

188
00:16:41,233 --> 00:16:43,322
- Kid, let's prep.
- Transport her.

189
00:16:45,739 --> 00:16:46,978
I'll go.

190
00:16:48,213 --> 00:16:49,424
Huh?

191
00:16:50,787 --> 00:16:54,574
Dr. Ashura, you should rest for a bit.

192
00:16:54,772 --> 00:16:56,191
No need.

193
00:16:56,192 --> 00:17:01,253
But normally, you'd be standing by
before the hotline even rings.

194
00:17:03,353 --> 00:17:07,633
You can't examine patients
properly in this state.

195
00:17:16,081 --> 00:17:20,090
Chika Komatsu, age 20.
She took the pills about 30 minutes ago.

196
00:17:20,115 --> 00:17:21,630
Stretcher coming through.

197
00:17:24,213 --> 00:17:25,473
Turning around.

198
00:17:29,645 --> 00:17:30,696
On three.

199
00:17:30,696 --> 00:17:31,905
One, two, three.

200
00:17:35,202 --> 00:17:37,523
Ms. Komatsu. Ms. Komatsu.

201
00:17:40,053 --> 00:17:42,732
- She's going in and out.
- Let's do a gastric lavage.

202
00:17:42,732 --> 00:17:45,583
Agreed. Get me
an 18-French nasogastric tube.

203
00:17:45,583 --> 00:17:46,847
Right away.

204
00:17:47,111 --> 00:17:49,957
Taishaku General Hospital

205
00:17:56,556 --> 00:17:59,478
Ms. Komatsu, you're awake.

206
00:18:03,046 --> 00:18:04,522
Why'd you save me?

207
00:18:04,926 --> 00:18:06,142
What?

208
00:18:06,199 --> 00:18:09,420
If you'd just left me alone,
I might've actually died this time.

209
00:18:09,420 --> 00:18:10,833
Ms. Komatsu, please calm...

210
00:18:10,833 --> 00:18:14,362
I never asked you to!
You did this on your own!

211
00:18:16,636 --> 00:18:21,885
Once a patient is brought to us,
we're obligated to save them.

212
00:18:23,031 --> 00:18:25,419
That's our job.

213
00:18:30,289 --> 00:18:32,135
I didn't want to be saved.

214
00:18:34,895 --> 00:18:37,931
I thought it'd finally all be over.
This is the worst!

215
00:18:38,641 --> 00:18:40,409
I don't wanna talk!

216
00:18:40,409 --> 00:18:42,587
Get out! Get out!

217
00:18:42,587 --> 00:18:43,779
Ms. Komatsu, okay.

218
00:18:43,779 --> 00:18:46,742
Shut up! I said get out!

219
00:18:46,782 --> 00:18:48,146
Let's step out for now.

220
00:19:00,898 --> 00:19:02,270
Doctor!

221
00:19:04,700 --> 00:19:10,277
I'm so sorry my husband said
those terrible things yesterday.

222
00:19:11,580 --> 00:19:14,980
And I also want to apologize
for what I said...

223
00:19:16,293 --> 00:19:19,202
Asking you to stop treatment.

224
00:19:19,202 --> 00:19:22,276
I'm so sorry. Please forgive me.

225
00:19:27,579 --> 00:19:31,444
The truth is, my husband is a doctor too.

226
00:19:34,415 --> 00:19:35,684
He is?

227
00:19:36,679 --> 00:19:41,912
As a palliative care physician,
he's watched over many patients' final days.

228
00:19:43,110 --> 00:19:50,854
That's exactly why I wanted to let him
have the kind of end he wished for.

229
00:19:54,097 --> 00:19:55,356
But still...

230
00:19:56,102 --> 00:20:01,096
I'm so glad he's alive.

231
00:20:03,533 --> 00:20:04,778
Doctor...

232
00:20:07,102 --> 00:20:12,464
Thank you so much
for saving my husband.

233
00:20:17,700 --> 00:20:19,257
He's not saved yet.

234
00:20:20,228 --> 00:20:21,428
What?

235
00:20:23,449 --> 00:20:27,159
Deep down, he wants to live.

236
00:20:31,483 --> 00:20:36,683
He's my patient.
I will never abandon him.

237
00:20:46,510 --> 00:20:47,775
Good work today.

238
00:20:47,797 --> 00:20:49,016
Good work.

239
00:20:49,971 --> 00:20:52,384
Oh, you're still here?

240
00:20:53,057 --> 00:20:57,297
I thought I'd check on Ms. Komatsu
before heading home.

241
00:20:57,803 --> 00:20:59,023
Huh?

242
00:20:59,240 --> 00:21:04,460
She kicked me out earlier,
but she may have calmed down by now.

243
00:21:05,089 --> 00:21:08,229
What if she kicks you out
again like before?

244
00:21:08,869 --> 00:21:10,117
Huh?

245
00:21:10,348 --> 00:21:14,711
Maybe leaving her alone for now
is what's best for her.

246
00:21:15,923 --> 00:21:19,935
You may be right that I should
just watch over her.

247
00:21:21,913 --> 00:21:28,344
But actually, I had a similar
patient once before.

248
00:21:30,230 --> 00:21:36,584
I didn't know how to connect with them,
so I discharged them once they stabilized.

249
00:21:39,372 --> 00:21:44,472
That night, the patient
was brought back in.

250
00:21:45,920 --> 00:21:49,943
This time, we couldn't save them.

251
00:21:54,908 --> 00:21:57,168
I still can't let go of that regret.

252
00:21:58,143 --> 00:22:05,324
If I'd just taken the time to listen,
maybe it wouldn't have ended that way.

253
00:22:08,509 --> 00:22:14,049
That's exactly why I can't just
leave Ms. Komatsu alone.

254
00:22:17,999 --> 00:22:20,632
You're a good man, Dr. Daikoku.

255
00:22:23,697 --> 00:22:27,939
I've never connected with patients
the way you do.

256
00:22:30,970 --> 00:22:34,946
But if you want to save her,

257
00:22:35,792 --> 00:22:40,684
I guess saying I can't
isn't really an option, is it?

258
00:23:06,709 --> 00:23:09,372
Stay away from that patient.

259
00:23:09,852 --> 00:23:15,376
Beyond that point lies hell for you, Anno.

260
00:23:34,413 --> 00:23:36,093
I told you not to come!

261
00:23:36,595 --> 00:23:42,119
Persistent, persistent Daikoku here.
But I'll be back again tomorrow.

262
00:24:03,752 --> 00:24:04,994
Um...

263
00:24:06,506 --> 00:24:07,744
Yes?

264
00:24:09,425 --> 00:24:11,841
Is this Chika Komatsu's room?

265
00:24:12,699 --> 00:24:15,739
It is. Are you a friend?

266
00:24:16,592 --> 00:24:22,065
More like a coworker.
She asked me to bring a change of clothes.

267
00:24:23,746 --> 00:24:26,443
She couldn't ask her family?

268
00:24:27,189 --> 00:24:28,802
I don't think so.

269
00:24:33,466 --> 00:24:37,669
Would you mind talking
with me for a bit?

270
00:24:40,499 --> 00:24:41,959
Sorry, out of the blue.

271
00:24:42,840 --> 00:24:45,069
My shift's not till tonight.

272
00:24:47,938 --> 00:24:50,778
Have you known Ms. Komatsu long?

273
00:24:51,553 --> 00:24:54,833
Not at all. We just chat
when we see each other at work.

274
00:24:55,940 --> 00:24:57,172
I see.

275
00:25:01,260 --> 00:25:03,212
Is Chika okay?

276
00:25:04,553 --> 00:25:07,213
Yeah. Physically, she's fine now.

277
00:25:10,470 --> 00:25:11,716
Thank God.

278
00:25:12,690 --> 00:25:14,736
I'm the one
who called the ambulance.

279
00:25:15,310 --> 00:25:16,602
You did?

280
00:25:17,950 --> 00:25:21,987
Chika called and said she took pills.
She sounded really bad.

281
00:25:24,050 --> 00:25:28,410
I see. Thanks to you,
she pulled through okay.

282
00:25:34,235 --> 00:25:37,930
But Ms. Komatsu said to us...

283
00:25:39,516 --> 00:25:41,816
that she didn't want to be saved.

284
00:25:45,106 --> 00:25:48,806
I've been a doctor
for quite a long time,

285
00:25:50,277 --> 00:25:52,724
but no one had ever
said that to me before.

286
00:25:55,890 --> 00:25:57,532
I was speechless.

287
00:26:05,252 --> 00:26:09,070
She doesn't really mean that,
about not wanting to be saved.

288
00:26:12,868 --> 00:26:19,896
She's just afraid of being rejected.
She thinks everyone will betray her.

289
00:26:22,813 --> 00:26:27,993
That makes her feel even emptier.
The pain outweighs the good.

290
00:26:29,899 --> 00:26:33,625
So she starts thinking, why bother
forcing yourself to keep living?

291
00:26:37,164 --> 00:26:42,194
But deep down,
she wants someone to save her.

292
00:26:46,543 --> 00:26:49,623
At least, that's what I assume she wants.

293
00:27:00,429 --> 00:27:01,972
I should get going.

294
00:27:02,736 --> 00:27:04,338
Thank you for talking to me.

295
00:27:18,690 --> 00:27:21,693
I'm glad you were moved
to the general ward.

296
00:27:22,140 --> 00:27:25,630
Hey, you might be discharged
pretty soon, right?

297
00:27:27,636 --> 00:27:28,978
Yeah.

298
00:27:32,036 --> 00:27:33,936
See you tomorrow, then.

299
00:27:35,523 --> 00:27:38,323
Sorry for all the trouble.

300
00:27:39,076 --> 00:27:42,036
I told you to stop apologizing.

301
00:27:42,076 --> 00:27:45,823
Well, good night.

302
00:27:45,823 --> 00:27:47,708
Good night.

303
00:27:50,156 --> 00:27:51,551
Yayoi.

304
00:27:51,976 --> 00:27:53,200
Hm?

305
00:27:53,443 --> 00:27:57,611
Have any of my patients
tried to contact me?

306
00:28:00,092 --> 00:28:06,816
No. Don't worry.
You handed them off already, right?

307
00:28:08,136 --> 00:28:09,632
Yeah, you're right.

308
00:28:10,689 --> 00:28:12,143
I'm heading home, then.

309
00:28:12,196 --> 00:28:14,094
- Good night.
- Good night.

310
00:28:14,176 --> 00:28:15,890
Be careful out there.

311
00:28:15,890 --> 00:28:17,128
I will.

312
00:28:28,755 --> 00:28:36,229
I thought saving a life
meant saving the patient.

313
00:28:38,186 --> 00:28:40,890
When you've been in emergency
medicine long enough,

314
00:28:41,389 --> 00:28:44,891
you learn it's not that simple.

315
00:28:46,894 --> 00:28:48,678
It's happened to me many times.

316
00:28:49,311 --> 00:28:56,743
Was it wrong of us to save
Mr. Hashimoto and Ms. Komatsu?

317
00:29:03,483 --> 00:29:06,360
Dr. Anno missed the hotline again.

318
00:29:06,375 --> 00:29:07,410
Yes?

319
00:29:07,410 --> 00:29:11,081
Female, 60s, severe shock from
traffic injuries. Requesting admission.

320
00:29:11,488 --> 00:29:13,348
Dr. Anno, what should we do?

321
00:29:13,610 --> 00:29:14,915
Accept her now.

322
00:29:24,373 --> 00:29:25,602
Hello?

323
00:29:29,479 --> 00:29:30,705
What?

324
00:29:33,024 --> 00:29:34,563
Stretcher coming through.

325
00:29:42,159 --> 00:29:43,558
Mrs. Hashimoto?

326
00:29:43,951 --> 00:29:45,173
Turning.

327
00:29:45,560 --> 00:29:46,802
Reversing.

328
00:29:47,620 --> 00:29:50,879
Get the pelvic binder on.
Prep transfusion and fluids.

329
00:30:02,243 --> 00:30:04,393
Blood pressure's dropping further.

330
00:30:06,454 --> 00:30:09,274
Massive intra-abdominal bleeding.
We gotta open her up.

331
00:30:09,274 --> 00:30:10,479
Okay.

332
00:30:10,610 --> 00:30:12,221
Y-Yayoi!

333
00:30:12,588 --> 00:30:14,235
Mr. Hashimoto!

334
00:30:14,235 --> 00:30:15,590
- Yayoi!
- Calm down!

335
00:30:15,590 --> 00:30:18,317
Answer me! Answer me!

336
00:30:19,110 --> 00:30:20,336
Mr. Hashimoto!

337
00:30:21,391 --> 00:30:22,424
Cardiac arrest!

338
00:30:22,424 --> 00:30:24,671
- Administer adrenaline.
- Yes, Doctor.

339
00:30:25,250 --> 00:30:27,027
Yayoi!

340
00:30:28,922 --> 00:30:31,106
Come on. Come on.

341
00:30:31,656 --> 00:30:33,216
Administering adrenaline.

342
00:30:34,594 --> 00:30:35,840
Come on.

343
00:30:37,303 --> 00:30:38,511
Come on.

344
00:30:39,709 --> 00:30:40,946
Come on.

345
00:30:41,749 --> 00:30:42,971
Come on.

346
00:30:43,494 --> 00:30:44,709
Come on.

347
00:30:45,349 --> 00:30:46,565
Come on.

348
00:30:46,955 --> 00:30:48,165
Come on.

349
00:30:48,355 --> 00:30:49,569
Come on.

350
00:30:49,876 --> 00:30:51,115
Two minutes.

351
00:31:11,595 --> 00:31:12,998
Heartbeat restored.

352
00:31:15,043 --> 00:31:16,253
Don't worry.

353
00:31:17,749 --> 00:31:19,771
I will get her out of this.

354
00:31:22,108 --> 00:31:24,129
No time for the OR.
We do it right here.

355
00:31:24,129 --> 00:31:26,412
- Get the laparotomy set.
- Yes, Doctor.

356
00:31:26,753 --> 00:31:28,490
- Scalpel.
- Here.

357
00:31:30,509 --> 00:31:32,130
- Retractor.
- Here.

358
00:31:40,036 --> 00:31:41,856
Finding the source and clamping it.

359
00:31:41,856 --> 00:31:43,043
- Suction here.
- Okay.

360
00:31:43,043 --> 00:31:44,264
- Towel.
- Here.

361
00:31:49,139 --> 00:31:51,587
Doctor, BP's in the 70s.

362
00:31:56,285 --> 00:31:57,503
Doctor.

363
00:32:01,060 --> 00:32:02,560
More transfusions, please.

364
00:32:02,560 --> 00:32:04,061
- Start pumping.
- Okay.

365
00:32:04,178 --> 00:32:05,833
- Satinsky clamp.
- Here.

366
00:32:07,540 --> 00:32:11,540
Dr. Anno usually would've
found it by now.

367
00:32:13,133 --> 00:32:14,923
The bleeding won't stop.

368
00:32:15,086 --> 00:32:16,606
We need to stop the bleeding!

369
00:32:16,606 --> 00:32:20,120
Too much bleeding from the liver.
I can't see the injury site.

370
00:32:20,120 --> 00:32:21,174
What?

371
00:32:21,174 --> 00:32:22,401
Keep suctioning.

372
00:32:22,899 --> 00:32:24,112
Yes, ma'am!

373
00:32:31,540 --> 00:32:33,015
BP's in the 50s!

374
00:32:33,432 --> 00:32:36,962
Doctor, if this keeps up,
she'll go into cardiac arrest again.

375
00:32:49,352 --> 00:32:50,852
There's too much bleeding.

376
00:32:51,600 --> 00:32:55,226
There's no way we can find
the source like this.

377
00:33:12,976 --> 00:33:14,197
Yayoi!

378
00:33:15,790 --> 00:33:17,492
Don't die on me!

379
00:33:19,683 --> 00:33:23,522
Not wanting to live anymore...
That was a lie!

380
00:33:24,970 --> 00:33:26,503
I want to be with you...

381
00:33:28,863 --> 00:33:33,163
I want so much more time
together with you!

382
00:33:34,590 --> 00:33:35,927
Yayoi!

383
00:33:38,430 --> 00:33:40,208
Yayoi!

384
00:34:14,633 --> 00:34:21,277
Is she searching for the source
by touch alone?

385
00:34:33,805 --> 00:34:35,091
Found it.

386
00:34:39,947 --> 00:34:42,181
The bleeding's stopped.

387
00:34:44,135 --> 00:34:45,606
BP is rising.

388
00:34:45,606 --> 00:34:48,282
- Dissect and protect it. Kelly clamp.
- Here.

389
00:35:22,061 --> 00:35:23,335
Thank you.

390
00:35:27,656 --> 00:35:31,431
Thank you for saving my wife. Truly.

391
00:35:33,915 --> 00:35:35,930
It's my job.

392
00:35:38,610 --> 00:35:40,679
She was fighting to survive.

393
00:35:42,462 --> 00:35:44,142
I just helped her do that.

394
00:35:48,350 --> 00:35:53,994
I've put Yayoi through
nothing but hardship all these years.

395
00:35:55,183 --> 00:36:00,023
I didn't want to be
a burden to her anymore.

396
00:36:00,596 --> 00:36:02,686
That's why you refused treatment.

397
00:36:04,609 --> 00:36:08,570
But deep down,
you still wanted to live.

398
00:36:10,776 --> 00:36:15,749
Your wife wanted you
to keep living too.

399
00:36:24,976 --> 00:36:26,727
Keep practicing medicine.

400
00:36:29,250 --> 00:36:31,856
Being a doctor is what
gives your life meaning.

401
00:36:34,420 --> 00:36:39,920
I can't. My body won't allow it anymore.

402
00:36:39,920 --> 00:36:44,547
Because of what you're going through,
you can understand patients like no one else.

403
00:36:48,367 --> 00:36:54,427
When you lie to your heart and deny
what you truly want, life loses its meaning.

404
00:36:56,825 --> 00:37:01,924
If you want to be a doctor,
then be one until your very last breath.

405
00:37:05,286 --> 00:37:06,500
As for me—

406
00:37:08,659 --> 00:37:13,419
Even with one foot in hell,
I'll keep saving patients.

407
00:37:22,560 --> 00:37:24,460
Hell, huh.

408
00:37:37,624 --> 00:37:39,764
You're right, Doctor.

409
00:37:41,144 --> 00:37:42,344
Yeah.

410
00:37:46,343 --> 00:37:47,877
Yayoi...

411
00:37:51,236 --> 00:37:53,780
Stay with me till the end.

412
00:38:18,446 --> 00:38:20,866
Clawed your way out of hell alone?

413
00:38:22,395 --> 00:38:26,517
As long as I have patients,
I won't run.

414
00:38:41,516 --> 00:38:42,549
Yes.

415
00:38:42,549 --> 00:38:46,257
Doctor, it's urgent.
Ms. Komatsu isn't in her room.

416
00:38:46,257 --> 00:38:47,290
What?

417
00:38:47,290 --> 00:38:49,270
Everyone's searching now.

418
00:38:50,716 --> 00:38:51,965
Got it.

419
00:38:52,409 --> 00:38:53,749
Ms. Komatsu!

420
00:38:57,015 --> 00:38:58,216
Did you find her?

421
00:38:58,216 --> 00:38:59,441
No.

422
00:39:01,019 --> 00:39:02,234
Ms. Komatsu!

423
00:39:21,693 --> 00:39:23,032
Where'd she go?

424
00:39:53,529 --> 00:39:54,782
Why are you here?

425
00:39:54,856 --> 00:39:56,913
I could ask you the same thing.

426
00:39:57,576 --> 00:39:58,709
None of your business.

427
00:39:58,709 --> 00:40:01,629
It is my business.
I'm your attending physician.

428
00:40:02,610 --> 00:40:03,907
Let go of me!

429
00:40:13,681 --> 00:40:18,705
Why? Why do you keep
getting in my way?

430
00:40:21,286 --> 00:40:23,024
It's just your job, right?

431
00:40:24,372 --> 00:40:28,049
You act all nice, but you're
just a stranger in the end.

432
00:40:30,080 --> 00:40:32,980
Nobody understands
what I'm going through.

433
00:40:35,486 --> 00:40:39,750
"You're just being weak,"
"try harder"...

434
00:40:40,741 --> 00:40:42,138
I don't wanna hear it.

435
00:40:48,388 --> 00:40:49,863
I can't do this anymore!

436
00:40:52,769 --> 00:40:55,158
Why does it always
have to be me?

437
00:40:57,149 --> 00:40:59,143
I want to end it all!

438
00:41:02,860 --> 00:41:08,708
I'm sorry, but I can't pretend
to understand how you feel.

439
00:41:11,906 --> 00:41:15,117
I don't even know what the right
medical response is here.

440
00:41:15,760 --> 00:41:20,634
So I can't give you
the words you're looking for.

441
00:41:27,106 --> 00:41:31,594
But I want you to live.

442
00:41:47,742 --> 00:41:49,682
You'll just leave anyway.

443
00:41:52,370 --> 00:41:53,776
Some people will, yes.

444
00:41:54,823 --> 00:41:56,123
But not me.

445
00:41:59,448 --> 00:42:02,748
Even if you push me away,
I'll stay by your side.

446
00:42:10,343 --> 00:42:12,636
My shift just ended, by the way.

447
00:42:23,513 --> 00:42:26,669
I'll stay with you as long as it takes.

448
00:43:08,833 --> 00:43:11,373
I'm so glad Ms. Komatsu is safe.

449
00:43:11,566 --> 00:43:14,096
Thank you, Dr. Naomi.

450
00:43:15,526 --> 00:43:18,446
I'm going to take time
to really connect with her.

451
00:43:18,866 --> 00:43:20,886
We'll be involved too.

452
00:43:24,193 --> 00:43:27,213
Thank you too, Dr. Ashura.

453
00:43:29,039 --> 00:43:30,519
I didn't do anything.

454
00:43:35,596 --> 00:43:37,256
Next up, our special feature.

455
00:43:37,956 --> 00:43:41,920
It's been 28 years since
the Wangan Station Stabbing Case.

456
00:43:42,737 --> 00:43:46,178
Our team has conducted
an exclusive follow-up investigation.

457
00:43:46,869 --> 00:43:53,569
In December 1997,
passersby were attacked indiscriminately.

458
00:43:53,729 --> 00:43:58,506
Three precious lives were lost
and over ten were injured.

459
00:43:59,110 --> 00:44:04,889
We spoke with Mr. Y, who lost
his beloved daughter in the attack.

460
00:44:10,610 --> 00:44:12,616
They can't identify them?

461
00:44:12,616 --> 00:44:15,503
I heard police were in the ICU.

462
00:44:15,569 --> 00:44:17,249
Doctor, what's wrong?

463
00:44:17,579 --> 00:44:20,192
Anno left in the middle of treatment?

464
00:44:20,459 --> 00:44:21,556
You're off this case.

465
00:44:21,556 --> 00:44:24,513
You heard, didn't you?
What I did back then.
